  "local_port": 54212,
  "remote_port": 443,
  "prompt": "How and when ISS was send to space?",
  "response": "The International Space Station (ISS) was not sent to space as a single entity. Instead, it was assembled in orbit through a series of launches and spacewalks over many years. Here\u2019s a brief overview of how and when the ISS was sent to space:\n\n### Assembly Timeline\n\n1. **Zarya Module (FGB)**:\n   - **Launch Date**: November 20, 1998\n   - **Launch Vehicle**: Proton rocket\n   - **Launch Site**: Baikonur Cosmodrome, Kazakhstan\n   - **Description**: The first component of the ISS, Zarya provided power, storage, propulsion, and guidance to the early stages of the station.\n\n2. **Unity Module (Node 1)**:\n   - **Launch Date**: December 4, 1998\n   - **Launch Vehicle**: Space Shuttle Endeavour (STS-88)\n   - **Launch Site**: Kennedy Space Center, Florida, USA\n   - **Description**: Unity was the first U.S.-built component of the ISS and connected to Zarya, forming the early structure of the station.\n\n3. **Zvezda Module (Service Module)**:\n   - **Launch Date**: July 12, 2000\n   - **Launch Vehicle**: Proton rocket\n   - **Launch Site**: Baikonur Cosmodrome, Kazakhstan\n   - **Description**: Zvezda provided living quarters, life support systems, and the capability for the station to be controlled from Earth.\n\n4. **Subsequent Modules**:\n   - Over the years, numerous other modules were launched and added to the ISS, including Destiny, Harmony, Tranquility, and various other components from participating countries like Japan, Europe, and Russia.\n\n### Key Assembly Phases\n\n- **Phase 1**: Early assembly (1998-2000) with Zarya, Unity, and Zvezda modules.\n- **Phase 2**: Core construction (2000-2006) with the addition of laboratories like Destiny, and other key components.\n- **Phase 3**: Outfitting and completion (2006-2011) with the addition of modules such as Harmony, Columbus, and Kibo, culminating with the installation of the Alpha Magnetic Spectrometer (AMS) and the final major components.\n\n### Continuous Operations\n\n- **First Crew**: The first long-duration crew, Expedition 1, arrived at the ISS on November 2, 2000.\n- **Continuous Human Presence**: The ISS has been continuously inhabited since then, with astronauts and cosmonauts rotating in shifts.\n\nThe assembly of the ISS required significant international cooperation and remains a testament to human ingenuity and the pursuit of space exploration.",
